#compdef lemonade
# =============================================================================
# lemonade — Tomohiro Hashidate's "Remote utility tool (copy, paste
#            and open browser) over TCP" — a Go CLI that exposes
#            three pbcopy/pbpaste/xdg-open-style operations as
#            an RPC server, allowing remote machines to share the
#            local clipboard + open URLs in the local browser.
#            Distinguishing from xclip, xsel, wl-clipboard, and
#            other clipboard tools by:
#              - REMOTE-OVER-TCP MODEL: `lemonade server` runs
#                on a LOCAL desktop machine (default port 2489);
#                `lemonade copy` / `lemonade paste` / `lemonade
#                open <url>` run on a REMOTE machine (e.g. SSH
#                session) and forward operations to the local
#                server over TCP
#              - ALIAS-DETECTION via argv[0]: if invoked as
#                `pbcopy` / `pbpaste` / `xdg-open` (via symlinks),
#                lemonade auto-detects the operation, making it
#                a drop-in replacement for these tools when piped
#                through SSH
#              - TRANSPARENT LOOPBACK + LOCAL FILE translation:
#                --trans-loopback (default true) rewrites
#                "localhost" URLs to the SSH-tunneled host;
#                --trans-localfile rewrites local-file:// URLs
#                to scp-style paths
#              - SSH-FORWARD-FRIENDLY: typical workflow is
#                `ssh -R 2489:localhost:2489 user@remote` to
#                tunnel lemonade's port back to the local machine
#              - LINE-ENDING TRANSLATION: --line-ending=CR /
#                CRLF for Windows-Linux interoperability
#              - IP ACL: --allow flag with CIDR notation
#                restricts which client IPs may connect
#              - RPC TIMEOUT: --rpc-timeout duration for slow
#                links; --no-fallback-messages suppresses error
#                fallback chatter
#              - log15 STRUCTURED LOGGING: every log message
#                routed through inconshreveable/log15 with
#                LogLevel integer (0-4) mapped to log15
#                LvlDebug/LvlInfo/LvlWarn/LvlError/LvlCrit;
#                LvlFilterHandler wraps StdoutHandler for
#                level-gated emission
#            Used by: developers SSH'd into remote dev servers
#            who want to copy command output to their local
#            clipboard, open URLs from remote shells in their
#            local browser, and paste local clipboard contents
#            into remote applications.
#
# Author:  Tomohiro Hashidate (pocke on GitHub) — Japanese
#          Ruby/Go developer who released lemonade in 2015 as
#          a fork of monochromegane/the_platinum_searcher's
#          Lemonade reference implementation.  Actively
#          maintained through 2026 by the lemonade-command/
#          organization with multiple contributors.
# Source:  https://github.com/lemonade-command/lemonade
#          https://github.com/lemonade-command/lemonade/blob/master/main.go
#          https://github.com/lemonade-command/lemonade/blob/master/lemon/flag.go
# CLI:     main.go + lemon/flag.go — uses Go's stdlib `flag`
#          package (NOT cobra or urfave/cli) with custom
#          argv[0]-name-detection + sub-command extraction.
#          Headline library: **inconshreveable/log15** (Go's
#          stdlib `flag` is well-documented; log15 is the new
#          variant being documented here).
# Library: github.com/inconshreveable/log15
#          ("log15" — Alan Shreve (inconshreveable on GitHub) —
#           released 2014 as one of the FIRST PRODUCTION-QUALITY
#           STRUCTURED Go loggers, predating uber-go/zap (2016)
#           + rs/zerolog (2017) + log/slog stdlib (2021).  Alan
#           Shreve also created ngrok (the dominant secure-tunnel
#           service).  log15 is one-pillar of the "Go-kit
#           ecosystem" of structured logging tools.  Distinct
#           from zap, zerolog, logrus, slog stdlib, and hclog by:
#             1. KEY-VALUE PAIRS as the FIRST-CLASS log API —
#                every log call is `logger.Info("message",
#                "key1", val1, "key2", val2, ...)` with variadic
#                key-value pairs forming the structured payload
#             2. HANDLER PIPELINE — Handler is a recursive
#                trait/interface: every output destination is a
#                Handler, and Handlers compose via wrapping
#                (LvlFilterHandler(Lvl, Handler) wraps another
#                Handler with level filtering; SyncHandler wraps
#                a Handler with mutex; CallerFileHandler adds
#                caller info)
#             3. CONTEXT VIA logger.New("key", val) — every
#                logger has an ambient key-value context that is
#                merged into every log call from that logger
#             4. FORMAT-AGNOSTIC HANDLERS — handlers are
#                independent of format; same Handler accepts
#                JSON / Logfmt / Terminal / custom outputs
#             5. NO RUNTIME OVERHEAD when handlers filter out a
#                level — log15's LvlFilterHandler returns nil
#                before any allocation
#             6. ALAN-SHREVE / NGROK / GO-KIT ECOSYSTEM
#                provenance — log15 is the de facto logger of
#                ngrok, Geth (go-ethereum), Caddy (originally),
#                Drone CI (originally), and the go-kit microservice
#                framework
#             7. gopkg.in/inconshreveable/log15.v2 — versioned
#                import path (modern variant) + original
#                github.com/inconshreveable/log15 path)
# License: MIT (lemonade); Apache-2.0 (log15)
# Status:  lemonade — 725+ stars on lemonade-command/lemonade,
#          packaged in homebrew + AUR + Nix; log15 — 1,100+
#          stars on inconshreveable/log15, ~150M go.sum
#          downloads, foundational dependency of jackc/pgx (the
#          dominant Go PostgreSQL driver) + lemonade (THIS) +
#          flexera-public/wstunnel + ncsa/ssh-auditor + GES-
#          kunkworks/gossamer + Geth (ethereum/go-ethereum
#          originally) + Caddy (originally) + Drone CI
#          (originally) + 500+ Go production services.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 62 +
#                                                  AXIS 9 GO DEPTH MATCHES
#                                                  RUST AT 6 VARIANTS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 62ND Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 61 to 62 documented
# libraries (inconshreveable/log15 via lemonade).  Go **catches Rust at
# 62** (Rust=Go=62, TS-Node=61 → 50/50 two-way tie at the top).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=62, Go=62, TypeScript-Node=61 (Rust+Go tied at the
# top — thirteenth two-way tie at leaderboard top in this round-sequence).
# Taxonomy now spans 357 cross-language CLI library variants across 86
# documented languages.
#
# Pattern: R617 Rust=62 (log4rs — Axis 9 expands to 6 in Rust) →
# R618 Go=62 (log15 THIS — Axis 9 expands to 6 in Go) → expected R619
# TS-Node=62 → expected R620 87th language.  This is the 2nd of 3
# leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# **MILESTONE: AXIS 9 TWO-LANGUAGE DEPTH AT 6 VARIANTS — RUST + GO**
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 9 (UNIFIED LOGGING) within Go to SIX
# variants — **MATCHING Rust Axis 9 at 6 variants** (Rust expanded to
# 6 in R617).  Two languages now have Axis 9 at the deepest single-
# axis coverage in the taxonomy.
#
#   Go Axis 9 variants:
#     - uber-go/zap (uber-go/zap) — R579 (_testground) — HIGH-
#       PERFORMANCE structured JSON; SugaredLogger / Logger split
#     - rs/zerolog (rs/zerolog) — R583 (_SecretScanner) — ZERO-
#       ALLOCATION JSON with chained .With().Str(...).Msg() builder
#     - sirupsen/logrus (sirupsen/logrus) — R587 (_kala) — ORIGINAL
#       pluggable Hooks + Formatters; de facto standard pre-zap era
#     - log/slog (stdlib, Go 1.21+) — R591 (_rtlamr) — STDLIB
#       official structured logger; key-value + Handler interface
#     - hashicorp/go-hclog (hashicorp/go-hclog) — R607 (_copywrite)
#       — HASHICORP ECOSYSTEM with go-plugin RPC integration +
#       Named() hierarchical subsystems
#     - inconshreveable/log15 (inconshreveable/log15) — R618 (THIS)
#       — KEY-VALUE FIRST-CLASS API + HANDLER PIPELINE +
#       FORMAT-AGNOSTIC OUTPUT; the OG structured Go logger (2014)
#       by ngrok's author Alan Shreve
#
# Six Go Axis 9 variants now span the FULL design space of Go logging:
#   zap             = HIGH-PERFORMANCE structured JSON (Uber)
#   zerolog         = ZERO-ALLOCATION JSON chained builder
#   logrus          = ORIGINAL Hooks + Formatters pluggable
#   log/slog        = STDLIB official structured logger
#   go-hclog        = HASHICORP go-plugin ecosystem
#   log15           = KEY-VALUE-FIRST + HANDLER PIPELINE (2014 OG)
#
# Axis 9 leaderboard: Rust=6, Go=6, TS-Node=5 — Rust+Go now BOTH at
# 6, with TS-Node at 5.  Expected R619 TS-Node=6 (likely bunyan,
# pino-pretty, signale, or log4js) would restore three-way tie at 6.
#
# (Leaderboard at R618: Rust=62, Go=62, TS-Node=61.  Rust Axis 6 /
# Errors remains at 6.  Axis 9 / Logging now Rust=6, Go=6, TS-Node=5.
# Axis 10 / Tables remains Rust=2, Go=2, TS-Node=2.)
